So if a vegetable (or whatever) isn‚Äôt having bugs eat it, maybe it has a genetic mutation that makes bugs not want it and we aren‚Äôt sure yet if there‚Äôs anything in those mutations that would be negative to our health. The color of eggs has absolutely no correlation to the quality or nutrition of the eggs. You are correct Nikole! As a home chicken grower for years, I can tell you what affects the quality/nutrition of the eggs is the diet of the chicken. We raise free range chickens and the quality of our eggs is so different from the basic eggs you get from the store. Our egg shells are green, blue, white, light brown, dark brown, and they all taste the same and the yolks are the same color because our chickens all have access to the same diet. Buy free range and you are getting the best eggs.

I do just want to add that organic doesn't mean chemical free. Organic fungicides and chemicals are used in significant levels and still need to be properly rinsed off. Additionally, organic food have a higher probability of bacterial contamination, like E.coli and Salmonella, and bug bites than genetically engineered foods. The residues from this could be carcinogenic when eaten raw over time. Cooking should get rid of most bacteria but it is important to always be careful with raw produce.
Edit: it should also be noted that many products labeled as Organic may be from other countries labeled in the fine print on the back, where the regulations for organic might be different. For example, I don't think the U.S. checks produce imports from China, which exports a lot of organic foods.

@Dreams Are Real Life   I am definitely no expert. I have, however, done quite a bit of research into organic vs non organic conventional vs GMO crops and I just want to help people make the most informed decision for themselves :) Almost every option has good and bad aspects to it. Unlike the other options, the downsides to Organic farming is not discussed very often. For example, organic fungicides and chemicals are not as well researched in terms of long term health impact as conventional pesticides. So, while we do know pesticides can cause some long term health issues, we don't yet have enough information to conclude that chemicals used on organics are completely safe. This, along with the things I mentioned before, show we should take the good in with the bad and find the healthiest way to prepare whatever we choose to buy, organic or not :)
